Tom,<br><br>
I to have never felt bitterness toward those who chose to stay behind or drive the war from a desk chair.  If they didn't throw it in my face I just didn't care.  It wasn't worth the effort.  I had better things to do.<br><br>
The Marines I know seem to suffer most.  They are all intense.  A sense of duty toward everything.  Not tolerant of rule breakers or lackadaisical attitudes.<br><br>
I have known some of the more prominent,such as Pappy Boyneton (sp) and his Nephew, also called Pappy and a Marine.  The nephew was in my test group.  All intense.  The loud ones were easy.  The quite ones scared the hell out of me at times.  One thing always.  Tell them the rules and the job and it was done.  The average guy off the street doesn't understand them.  None I have known ever forget including one POW from Korea who weighed 200+ when captured and 87 when released.  It is part of what makes them Marines.<br><br>
Cook is my friend also, because I respect what he is, a man of duty.
